article.description:
Chasity Melvin had 17 points and seven rebounds to lead the host Washington Mystics to a 65-63 victory Tuesday
night over the Charlotte Sting, losers of a franchise record nine straight games.
article.headline: Mystics gain 4-0 sweep of Charlotte this season
article.linkText: Sting drop franchise-record ninth in a row
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chasity Melvin had 17 points and seven
rebounds to lead the Washington Mystics to a 65-63 victory Tuesday
night over the Charlotte Sting, losers of a franchise record nine
straight games.

The Mystics (13-12) completed a four-game season sweep of the
Sting (3-21), who dropped to 0-12 on the road this season.

Tangela Smith had a season-high 25 points and eight rebounds for
Charlotte.

"I have to thank my teammates tonight," Smith said. "They
were the ones who found me and got me in position for the
baskets."

Delisha Milton-Jones scored 12 points and reserves Murriel Page
and Coco Miller added 10 apiece for the Mystics, who opened a
three-game homestand and moved two games ahead of Detroit and a
half-game ahead of New York in the Eastern Conference.

"Tonight, Houston just beat Detroit by a buzzer and New York
lost to Connecticut," Mystics coach Richie Adubato said. "That
helps us because we pick a game up on each one of our
competitors."

Jia Perkins' turnaround jumper pulled the Sting to 63-60 with
16.2 seconds remaining. After Melvin missed the second of two free
throws with 14.7 seconds left, Tammy Sutton-Brown rebounded and
called timeout for Charlotte.

Perkins' 3-pointer from the right wing pulled the Sting to 64-63
with 4.4 seconds left. Washington rookie Temeka Johnson was fouled
on the ensuing inbounds play and made the first of two free throws
for a 65-63 lead with 4.4 seconds left.

Kelly Mazzante's desperation 3-pointer bounced off the side of
the backboard as the final horn sounded.

"I felt like we shouldn't have been in that situation," Melvin
said. "Nothing against Charlotte, but we were playing at home and
I felt like we came out too relaxed in the second half."

"We are trying to make a playoff run, so we will take them no
matter how difficult they may be or how easy the game may be,"
Milton-Jones added.

Perkins finished with a career-high six assists. Helen Darling
had season-highs of 11 points and seven assists before fouling out.

Charlotte was playing for the first time since trading
three-time All-Star point guard Dawn Staley to Houston late Monday
night.

"This is an opportunity I've been waiting for," Darling said
of taking over as the starting point guard. "I just need to get to
the point where my teammates can trust me."

Alana Beard, the Mystics' leading scorer averaging 15.1 points,
scored four points on 1-for-13 shooting. Rookie Temeka Johnson
finished with seven points and six assists.

"I thought containing the two guards spoke words for our
defensive effort," Sting coach Trudi Lacey said. "But the Mystics
got production and big plays from Page and Miller, who came off the
bench and played well."

Sheri Sam, who is two field goals shy of 1,000 during her
career, hit a jumper that pulled the Sting within 44-41 midway
through the second half.

Melvin scored five points during Washington's 7-0 run to a 30-18
lead late in the first half. Miller had four points during a 6-0
run as the Mystics took control earlier in the game.
